cent and alliance are basic forms of relatedness that have received unequal attention in social anthropology. Offering new insights into the ways in which friendship is conceptualized and realized in various sub-Saharan African settings, the contributions to this volume depart from the recent tendency to study friendship in isolation from kinship. In drawing attention to the complexity of the interactions between these two kinds of social relationships, the book suggests that analyses of friendship in Western societies would also benefit from research that explores more systematically friendship in conjunction with kinship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aFriendshipzAfrica, Sub-Saharan. 0aKinshipzAfrica, Sub-Saharan. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBreusers, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiallo, Youssouf, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrätz, Tilo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrätz, Tilo, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGuichard, Martine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuichard, Martine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKlute, Georg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReyna, Stephen P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchlee, Günther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpencer, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTadesse, Wolde Gossa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWarms, Richard L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWerbner, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.